			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hmm I don't know if you can do this in MySQL, but in PostgreSQL you can convert time from one time zone to another..
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">ao=&gt; SELECT '2003-10-22 02&#58;53&#58;10 UTC' AT TIME ZONE 'EST';
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; timezone
<br />
---------------------
<br />
&nbsp;2003-10-21 21&#58;53&#58;10
<br />
&#40;1 row&#41;</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
You can also set the TZ(time zone) env variable before using date functions in PHP, eg:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">&lt;?
<br />
&nbsp; putenv&#40;&quot;TZ=EST&quot;&#41;;
<br />
&nbsp; printf&#40;&quot;EST&#58; %s\n&quot;, date&#40;&quot;r&quot;&#41;&#41;;
<br />
&nbsp; putenv&#40;&quot;TZ=GMT&quot;&#41;;
<br />
&nbsp; printf&#40;&quot;GMT&#58; %s\n&quot;, date&#40;&quot;r&quot;&#41;&#41;;
<br />
?&gt;
<br />

<br />
EST&#58; Sat, 22 Nov 2003 03&#58;55&#58;31 -0500
<br />
GMT&#58; Sat, 22 Nov 2003 08&#58;55&#58;31 +0000</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Not sure if that works under windows though.. :P</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
