			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The nightmare shouldn't be as bad as you think...
<br />

<br />
I would store a timezone per user, and a default 'convert to' timezone (say agreed org timezone, or UTC).
<br />

<br />
Did some experimenting in perl, this should be possible the other way around as well (don't know the specifics in php).
<br />
[edit] I just saw Dinkles describe the php-way to do it. Even if there is no inverse function in php, you could get a proper, DST-adjusted offset by subtracting time-(localized time).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">#! /usr/bin/perl -w
<br />

<br />
$ENV&#123;TZ&#125; = 'GMT';
<br />
print localtime&#40;&#41;.&quot;\n&quot;;
<br />

<br />
$ENV&#123;TZ&#125; = 'CET';
<br />
print localtime&#40;&#41;.&quot;\n&quot;;
<br />

<br />
$ENV&#123;TZ&#125; = 'UTC';
<br />
print localtime&#40;&#41;.&quot;\n&quot;;</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
...this prints out...</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">Thu Nov 27 15&#58;27&#58;59 2003
<br />
Thu Nov 27 16&#58;27&#58;59 2003
<br />
Thu Nov 27 15&#58;27&#58;59 2003</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
So by setting the TZ shell variable (this is Linux as well, so check the vars on your windows system) the system-time gets converted to a time suitable for your timezone. Simply set TZ before your time-construction call (from 4:34PM or whatever) and you get a nice system time, which you can convert back to whatever TZ needed.
<br />

<br />
regards,
<br />

<br />
Wozza<br />_________________<br />:wq</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
